    "body": "No, @alwx I am not talking about telling user that sync is done before it is done. \r\n\r\nWith LES (light ethereum) protocol, we start with some \"safe point/block\" and from that point pulling blockchain headers, up until the current block (at this moment, sync is done). From time to time, that safe point is updated (by Geth team, safe point is hard-coded), so that syncing is not from zero to the current block. \r\n\r\nSo, I wanted to explore the ways for us to set that \"safe point\" i.e. what instead of using starting block that is 10000 blocks away from the current, we are to start with a block that is, say, 100 blocks away (thus full sync will be faster, as only headers for those 100 blocks will be pulled). \r\n\r\nI can incorporate that setting of the starting block to the `!reset` command (command I am working on atm, it will allow to reset chaindata folder). This will give us two things: \r\n - resetting will be cheap, as re-sync will be relatively fast \r\n - re-sync will be only manually triggered on reset (so that if everything is intact we do not force users to sync, even those 100 blocks).\r\n\r\n**N.B.** Please note that I have little idea on why sync stalls on 0%, and my solution is although related to the original issue, is most probably not the exact fix for the issue (the aim is just improve sync experience overall, and adding that suggestion to this issue seemed appropriate).",
